        <body>
            <head>190. Memorandum From Secretary of State <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu"
                    >Vance</persName> to President <persName corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8"
                    >Carter</persName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d190fn1">Source: Carter Library,
                    National Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, Brzezinski Office File, Country
                    Chron File, Box 50, <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName>.
                    Confidential. There is no indication <persName corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8"
                        >Carter</persName> saw the memorandum.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1977-07-06"
                        >July 6, 1977</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>Waiver of the $40 Million Ceiling on <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 1977
                        <rs type="topic" corresp="recoKawZ2IOcE8nyB">Military Assistance</rs>,
                    Credits and Guaranties for African Countries, under Section 33(b) of the <rs
                        type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recf7oWPDGyUlNNf7">Arms Export Control
                        Act</rs>, as amended</item>
            </list>
            <p>This memorandum asks you to exercise your authority under section 33(b) of the <rs
                    type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recf7oWPDGyUlNNf7">Arms Export Control
                    Act</rs> to waive the $40 million statutory ceiling on the total (excluding
                training) of grant <rs type="topic" corresp="recoKawZ2IOcE8nyB">military
                    assistance</rs> and <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">foreign
                    military sales</rs> (<gloss target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss>) credits and guaranteed loans to African countries in fiscal year 1977. The
                waiver of the ceiling is urgently needed to permit implementation of <gloss
                    target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss> financing programs, especially to make progress payments on prior
                purchases.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">Background</p>
            <p>Section 33 (a) of the <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recf7oWPDGyUlNNf7"
                    >Arms Export Control Act</rs>, as amended, imposes an annual $40 million ceiling
                on <rs type="topic" corresp="recoKawZ2IOcE8nyB">military assistance</rs> and <gloss
                    target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss> financing for African countries. Section 33 (b) of the Act provides that
                you may waive this ceiling when you determine that a waiver is important to the
                security of the United States, and promptly so report to the <orgName
                    corresp="recmLoDjMiF4yt3cM">Congress</orgName>.</p>
            <p>The $40 million ceiling has ceased to be a realistic limitation and has been waived
                successively in recent years. Last year, the Ford Administration justified to
                    <orgName corresp="recmLoDjMiF4yt3cM">Congress</orgName>
                <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 1977 <rs type="topic" corresp="recfsYEHWUfhmWQY2"
                    >security assistance</rs> programs for <placeName corresp="rech4Y08vWrfyBSYC"
                    >Africa</placeName> which exceeded the $40 million ceiling by more than $60
                million. In <placeName corresp="reco2M6RfIym93BJO">North Africa</placeName> alone
                our program justifications for <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl"
                    >Morocco</placeName> and <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj"
                    >Tunisia</placeName> exceed the ceiling. Subsequent reprogramming has only
                slightly increased the total African program.</p>
            <p>Although <orgName corresp="recmLoDjMiF4yt3cM">Congress</orgName> declined last year
                to repeal the ceiling, it approved the requested funding levels. This <orgName
                    corresp="recmLoDjMiF4yt3cM">Congressional</orgName> action appears to assume
                that the ceiling again will be waived. <orgName corresp="recmLoDjMiF4yt3cM"
                    >Congress</orgName>, therefore, should expect you to waive this limitation in
                order to implement country programs at the levels it has approved. We will report
                your determination to <orgName corresp="recmLoDjMiF4yt3cM">Congress</orgName> on
                your behalf and provide it with the attached justification,<note n="2" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d190fn2">Not attached.</note> as has been the practice with previous
                determinations.</p>
            <pb facs="0477" n="456" xml:id="pg_456"/>
            <p>As shown in the table at Tab 1,<note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d190fn3">Not
                    attached.</note> our planned <gloss target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss> financing in <placeName corresp="rech4Y08vWrfyBSYC">Africa</placeName> for
                    <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 1977 consists of <gloss target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss> programs for seven countries—<placeName corresp="recfpFrNXC2mjKxLP"
                    >Zaire</placeName>, <placeName corresp="recDrp9EcYwDe8lHj">Senegal</placeName>,
                    <placeName corresp="recJYKsUtxDe7TEqq">Liberia</placeName>, <placeName
                    corresp="recr6k8TVXxEPlyr5">Gabon</placeName>, <placeName
                    corresp="recw9a0yXk1ACb6to">Kenya</placeName>, <placeName
                    corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName>, and <placeName
                    corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName>. These programs total about
                $108.5 million.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">Arms Control Considerations</p>
            <p>The waiving of the $40 million African ceiling will not conflict with your recently
                announced policy to restrain conventional <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="rec9ptkWICFUk7Mvu">arms transfers</rs>. The <gloss target="#t_FY_1"
                    >FY</gloss> 1977 <gloss target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss> financing programs for African countries will be used to finance purchases
                of <rs type="topic" corresp="recOz4p561G66Gv2s">defense articles</rs> and services
                by countries whose defense is important to the security of the United States and
                whose unfriendly neighbors are armed with superior weapons. Consequently, the sales
                which result from waiving this $40 million ceiling should not adversely affect
                regional distributions of power or promote arms races in <placeName
                    corresp="rech4Y08vWrfyBSYC">Africa</placeName>.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">Publication</p>
            <p>Section 654 (c) of the <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recQ7wNs9H53qbIlS"
                    >Foreign Assistance Act of 1961</rs>, as amended, requires that the waiver be
                published in the <hi rendition="simple_italic">Federal Register</hi> unless you
                conclude that such publication would be “harmful to the national security of the
                United States.” Since the program levels are public knowledge, publication in this
                case would have no harmful effect on the national security.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">Recommendation:</p>
            <p>I recommend that you approve and sign the determination at Tab 2, and thereby approve
                the attached justification.<note n="4" place="foot" xml:id="d190fn4">Tab 2 is not
                    attached. There is no indication of approval or disapproval of the
                    recommendation, but see <ref target="#d191">Document 191</ref>.</note> The
                    <orgName corresp="recjQ97iMHKp6vwlA">Department of Defense</orgName> concurs in
                this determination.</p>
        </body>
